post_text:
This is a reminder from the City of Chelsea that your community needs you to complete the 2020 Census. So far, only 52% of Chelsea households have responded.

We have just one month left to ensure that every person living in Chelsea is counted. The deadline for the Census is Sept. 30th. Please complete the Census AS SOON AS POSSIBLE.

Census workers with a census taker badge will be visiting the homes of families that have not yet been counted. They will not ask questions about your immigration status. If you do not want a visit, please do the census yourself by visiting my2020census.gov today. Or, you can stop by City Hall for assistance.

post_text:
Dear Parents,

We regret to inform you that due to the ongoing impact and safety concerns regarding COVID 19, the Early Learning Center will be unable to run the Half Day Pre-Kindergarten Program for the 2020-2021 school year.

In place of the Half Day Pre-Kindergarten Program, the ELC will be providing online resources for all Pre-Kindergarten age students. These resources will be available on the Chelsea Public Schools website and will consist of weekly video lessons, story times, and activities that families can access at any time of the day.

The online resources will be available beginning September 23, 2020. Further information about how to access the resources will be forthcoming.

We are deeply saddened that we will not be able to work in person with you and your children this year and we look forward to being more connected next year in Kindergarten.

Stay safe, healthy and connected.

Sincerely,

Jacqueline Bevere
Principal

post_text:
An additional $199.50 in food benefits was automatically added to each P-EBT card in the end of June. Families can now use these additional funds.

Important information to share with the families:
The $199.50 will help cover the school meals missed due to closures from COVID-19 from May through June

Families do NOT need a new P-EBT card. If families have lost their P-EBT card or did not receive one, they should visit www.MAp-EBT.org

Families do NOT need to reactivate their card again

Families can check their balance by calling the number on the back of their card

Eligible DTA clients should have received all of their P-EBT benefits as of June. If families have not received all of their P-EBT benefits by June, they should call the DTA Assistance Line at 877-382-2363

post_text:
If your family already qualifies for free or reduced price school meals under the National School Lunch Program, you automatically will receive P-EBT benefits. This includes any student in a school that provides free meals to all students.

Households will receive $5.70 per eligible student per day, or $28.50 a week. If receiving DTA benefits, your P-EBT benefits will be added to your existing EBT card. If not actively receiving DTA benefits, you will receive a P-EBT card in the mail for each eligible student in your household.

You will be getting a letter in the mail from DTA in late May/early June. If you do not get a letter in the mail by this time and your child received free or reduced price school meals, contact Project Bread‚Äôs FoodSource Hotline at (800) 645-8333 (TTY 800-377-1292).

post_text:
Dear Parents/Guardians,

This message is only for students moving up to a new school including Kindergarten and grade 1 students at ELC, grade 4 students at the Complex, and grades 4 and 6 Kelly School Caminos Program. As we plan for the next school year we are providing you with an opportunity to indicate a preferred school for your child for next year. For families wishing to request a change of school, please reach out to PIC after the last day of school.

Please go to the Parent Information Center website at https://www.chelseaschools.com/Page/2627 to complete the appropriate form by Friday, May 22. You will be informed of your child‚Äôs school assignment on the last day of school. If you have any questions or concerns, please call the Parent Information Center at 617.466.5500.

Please be advised:
Student placements are based on program needs, siblings, available space and the remaining students will be placed in a lottery.
Every effort will be made to assign your child to your preferred school however, we do not guarantee you will receive your first preference.

Over the next few weeks, the City will be making changes to its food distribution program. Starting next week, there will be only one pop-up food pantry location Mon. to Thursday, and then two locations on Fri. The locations are as follows:

Mon. May 18: Corner of Congress and Hawthorne (Quigley Park)
Tues. May 19: Bellingham Hill Park
Wed. May 20: Washington Sq. Park
Thurs. May 21: Chelsea Square
Fri. May 22: both City Hall and Mary C Burke

Starting the following week, the week of May 25th, all food distribution will be relocated to a single location ‚Äì the food distribution site on Marginal Street across from PORT Park. Because Mon. May 25 is a Holiday, there will be no food distribution that day. That Holiday week only, food distribution will occur at the Marginal St. location starting at 11:00 a.m. on Tues. May 26, Wed. May 27 and Fri. May 29. After that week, starting on June 1st, food distribution will take place at this Marginal St. location across from PORT Park, every Mon., Wed. and Fri. at 11:00 a.m. until further notice.

Hi Central Team ‚Äî
Just writing to bring you a smile on a rainy Monday morning!

Kelly the Dolphin (who got lonely at school and is staying with my family for the duration) and Kelly School teachers got a little fancy to welcome kids back to learning after April break! Here‚Äôs the short video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C7e1TempYZA

We also encouraged kids to dress up in something that makes them feel happy and comfortable as they get back to their learning work today!

I just also want to say how much I and my team appreciate the support, guidance, responsiveness, and proactive approach that the entire CPS central team has shown throughout this unexpected twist to our school year. As I talk with colleagues from other districts and other states, it‚Äôs again and again been clear that this team is ahead of the curve in the speed, intentionality and heart with which you have tackled everything from food and chromebook distribution to instructional guidance ‚Äî thank you.
cheers,
LL

post_text:
Good morning,

Starting today, the emergency school food program will move to three days per week - Monday, Wednesday, and Friday. Families will be able to pick up two days of breakfasts and lunch at a time on these days. This will allow us to add an extra day's worth of food each week and will reduce the number of trips each family has to make. As always, students do not need to be present for a family to be able to pick up food. There will be no more food service on Tuesdays and Thursdays here forward. Please see the District website for more details.

LEWIS LATIMER SOCIETY & MUSEUM

A Museum that seeks to understand American History through the lens of the African American experience.

THE EARLY DAYS OF AFRICAN AMERICANS IN CINEMA

African Americans have had a long and rather complex history in the American motion picture industry. Early depictions of African Americans men and women were confined to demeaning stereotypical images of people of color. During the first decades of the 20th century many films depicted a nostalgic and idealized vision of life in the antebellum South.

WHEN: SUNDAY, FEBRUARY 16, 2020

WHERE: FIRST CONGREGRATIONAL CHURCH
26 COUNTY ROAD
CHELSEA MA.

TIME:12:30-2:30 PM

THE PROGRAM & DISCUSSION IS FREE AND OPEN TO THE PUBLIC

DAVID HILL IS PRESENTER AND RESEARCHER!

LIGHT REFRESHMENTS WILL BE SERVED!

post_text:
Dear Parents and Guardians:

At 7:55 am this morning, Chelsea police called to report shots fired in the areas of Fifth Street and Chestnut Street. Because the police did not have any information on what was transpiring and students were still walking to school, I felt the safest course of action was to call an Administrative Lockdown for the three middle schools, the ELC, and Chelsea High School. The lockdown was lifted at 8:08 am.

It turns out that the construction company in the area caused the shot spotter to register as gun fire. This lockdown was done as precautionary only and at no time were staff or students in danger.

I thank Chelsea police and our educators for their quick actions this morning.

Yours,

Mary
